      <p class="MsoNormal">
        <br clear="all" style="mso-special-character:line-break;page-break-before:always"/>
      </p>
      <div class="Section3">
        <a name="_19f92250-69c4-f13b-d2e4-95897e2a7f31" id="_19f92250-69c4-f13b-d2e4-95897e2a7f31"></a>
        <h1 class="Annex"><b>Annex B</b><br/>(informative)<br/><b>Relationship with OGC Features and Observations</b></h1>
        <div><a name="_ba6c5d0e-75da-ed7f-b9ed-74e4fd9e9ca8" id="_ba6c5d0e-75da-ed7f-b9ed-74e4fd9e9ca8"></a><h2>B.1.<span style="mso-tab-count:1">&#xA0; </span>Overview</h2>

<p class="MsoNormal"><a name="_de5e3ac9-7117-e588-fe84-9f921fd26f93" id="_de5e3ac9-7117-e588-fe84-9f921fd26f93"></a>EmissionML is a domain-specific conceptual model that builds on two foundational OGC concepts: <b>Features</b> (ISO 19109 General Feature Model) and <b>Observations</b> (ISO/OGC 19156:2023, OMS 3.0). This annex explains how EmissionML relates to each and why explicit domain modeling is preferred over generic usage.</p>

<p class="MsoNormal"><a name="_c7a5fdc9-86ae-c660-8d83-8e8954f18031" id="_c7a5fdc9-86ae-c660-8d83-8e8954f18031"></a><a href="#fig-annex-b-layering">Figure B.1</a> illustrates the conceptual layering of EmissionML on top of these foundational standards.</p>

<div class="figure"><a name="fig-annex-b-layering" id="fig-annex-b-layering"></a>

<p class="figure" style="page-break-after:avoid;"><img src="cid:db15c166-a576-4a5d-bdda-3eda6da71b5d.png" height="225" width="489"/></p><p class="FigureTitle" style="text-align:center;">Figure B.1&#xA0;&#x2014; Conceptual layering of EmissionML on foundational ISO/OGC standards</p></div>
</div>
        <div><a name="_76d8e162-2c4b-9199-ab7a-05313e7b579a" id="_76d8e162-2c4b-9199-ab7a-05313e7b579a"></a><h2>B.2.<span style="mso-tab-count:1">&#xA0; </span>EmissionML and OGC Features</h2>

<p class="MsoNormal"><a name="_5b6a0ebd-81ad-b975-1def-aaae8a9c937a" id="_5b6a0ebd-81ad-b975-1def-aaae8a9c937a"></a>The OGC General Feature Model (ISO 19109) defines a <i>Feature</i> as an abstraction of a real-world phenomenon &#x2014; any entity with an identity, properties, and optionally a geometry. EmissionML makes this alignment explicit by introducing a concrete <b>Feature</b> class (stereotyped <tt>&lt;&lt;ISO 19109&gt;&gt;</tt>) into the conceptual model.</p>

<p class="MsoNormal"><a name="_902da3ec-8a16-840f-edbf-ab183289ebc8" id="_902da3ec-8a16-840f-edbf-ab183289ebc8"></a>The Feature class carries a mandatory <tt>geometry</tt> attribute of type <tt>GM_Object</tt> and serves as the base class for domain-specific feature types. <b>Source</b> inherits from Feature, gaining its geometry by inheritance. This structural inheritance &#x2014; rather than a notional stereotype &#x2014; makes the ISO 19109 alignment unambiguous and machine-verifiable.</p>

<p class="MsoNormal"><a name="_d22c73c9-22c3-e359-6ce5-1a84cb24d69f" id="_d22c73c9-22c3-e359-6ce5-1a84cb24d69f"></a>Because Feature is concrete, an Observation&#x2019;s <tt>ultimateFeatureOfInterest</tt> can reference any Feature &#x2014; not only a Source. This enables observations whose feature of interest is defined at a different spatial scale (e.g., a facility area, a region, or a monitoring zone) to participate in the evidence chain without being forced into the Source class.</p>

<p class="MsoNormal"><a name="_e3c74feb-e5f4-6df1-bd93-d3b6a9fc259e" id="_e3c74feb-e5f4-6df1-bd93-d3b6a9fc259e"></a><b>EmissionEvent</b> is also a real-world phenomenon &#x2014; an occurrent that unfolds over time. In principle, an Emission Event <i>could</i> be modeled as a generic Feature. However, EmissionML gives it explicit structure: temporal bounds (start time, end time), a quantity of emitted substance, a mechanism describing the physical or operational process, an intent classification, and an evidence chain linking the event to supporting Observations.</p>

<p class="MsoNormal"><a name="_5f68f7b7-67b5-c660-5337-844f8cda77a9" id="_5f68f7b7-67b5-c660-5337-844f8cda77a9"></a>Without this explicit modeling, a Source would be indistinguishable from any other Feature, and an emission event would be &#x201C;just another Feature&#x201D; with ad-hoc properties. The semantic relationships that give emission data its meaning &#x2014; <tt>hasSource</tt>, <tt>hasMechanism</tt>, <tt>hasQuantity</tt>, <tt>hasStartTimeEvidence</tt> &#x2014; would be lost or require convention-based interpretation.</p>
</div>
        <div><a name="_40f678bc-0bd3-d0c2-7d52-eb32ff37b29b" id="_40f678bc-0bd3-d0c2-7d52-eb32ff37b29b"></a><h2>B.3.<span style="mso-tab-count:1">&#xA0; </span>EmissionML and OMS 3.0 Observations</h2>

<p class="MsoNormal"><a name="_5e8931c5-0947-ecf7-e6b7-5a3e19e5fccb" id="_5e8931c5-0947-ecf7-e6b7-5a3e19e5fccb"></a>OMS 3.0 (ISO/OGC 19156:2023) defines an Observation as an act of determining the value of an observable property. An Observation has a well-defined structure: a feature of interest, an observed property, a procedure, and a result.</p>

<p class="MsoNormal"><a name="_63a706eb-7b86-0aae-f71d-e67a4e297414" id="_63a706eb-7b86-0aae-f71d-e67a4e297414"></a>EmissionML incorporates OMS 3.0 Observation <b>by reference</b> (Requirement 8) &#x2014; it does not redefine or extend the Observation class. In EmissionML, Observations serve as <b>evidence</b> supporting emission quantity and temporal bound determinations, linked through the <tt>hasQuantityEvidence</tt>, <tt>hasStartTimeEvidence</tt>, and <tt>hasEndTimeEvidence</tt> associations.</p>

<p class="MsoNormal"><a name="_f80bcce6-62d3-e023-19bf-565b54e2b3ed" id="_f80bcce6-62d3-e023-19bf-565b54e2b3ed"></a>One might ask: <i>Why not model the entire emission event as an Observation result?</i> Because an Emission Event is richer than what a single Observation captures. An Emission Event has a source, a mechanism, an intent, multiple temporal bounds, and can be supported by <i>multiple</i> Observations at different spatial and temporal scales. For example:</p>

<div class="ul_wrap"><p style="mso-list:l3 level1 lfo8;" class="MsoListParagraphCxSpFirst"><a name="_b7cd5bba-1c6d-1882-5ab4-09e2dec5f32a" id="_b7cd5bba-1c6d-1882-5ab4-09e2dec5f32a"></a>A satellite remote sensing Observation may detect a methane plume over a broad area.
</p>
<p style="mso-list:l3 level1 lfo8;" class="MsoListParagraphCxSpMiddle"><a name="_1726aecd-87f8-10ab-a209-37a5d57545f1" id="_1726aecd-87f8-10ab-a209-37a5d57545f1"></a>An Optical Gas Imaging (OGI) camera Observation may pinpoint the leak to a specific component.
</p>
<p style="mso-list:l3 level1 lfo8;" class="MsoListParagraphCxSpLast"><a name="_d88d4fa4-1f4b-af23-d642-87ab05910f14" id="_d88d4fa4-1f4b-af23-d642-87ab05910f14"></a>A continuous emissions monitoring system (CEMS) Observation may quantify the emission rate over time.
</p>
</div>

<p class="MsoNormal"><a name="_0f0956fd-edbc-f42b-b8c5-b66972fa2549" id="_0f0956fd-edbc-f42b-b8c5-b66972fa2549"></a>All three Observations can serve as evidence for a single Emission Event, each contributing to the determination of quantity, start time, or end time. The Observation&#x2019;s <tt>ultimateFeatureOfInterest</tt> references a Feature &#x2014; which may be a Source or any other Feature at a different spatial scale. The satellite Observation&#x2019;s feature of interest may be a Feature representing an entire facility, while the OGI Observation&#x2019;s feature of interest is a Source representing a single valve.</p>
</div>
        <div><a name="_bc546e58-6030-3b56-c64e-7e863f299ebd" id="_bc546e58-6030-3b56-c64e-7e863f299ebd"></a><h2>B.4.<span style="mso-tab-count:1">&#xA0; </span>EmissionML and OMS 3.0 Procedures</h2>

<p class="MsoNormal"><a name="_923cabde-9271-765d-92e6-3e4b2c1255dd" id="_923cabde-9271-765d-92e6-3e4b2c1255dd"></a>OMS 3.0 defines a <b>Procedure</b> as &#x201C;a description of steps performed&#x201D; and introduces <b>ObservingProcedure</b> as a specialization that describes steps performed to determine the value of an observable property. EmissionML follows this same specialization pattern.</p>

<p class="MsoNormal"><a name="_af6d4a34-0431-f54e-857a-3b3307a9cefb" id="_af6d4a34-0431-f54e-857a-3b3307a9cefb"></a>The EmissionML conceptual model introduces a <b>Procedure</b> class (stereotyped <tt>&lt;&lt;ISO 19156:2023&gt;&gt;</tt>) as the base class for process descriptions. <b>DeterminationProcedure</b> inherits from Procedure and describes the steps performed to determine a value &#x2014; such as an emission quantity or temporal bound. This structural inheritance mirrors how ObservingProcedure specializes Procedure in OMS 3.0.</p>

<p class="MsoNormal"><a name="_cf801897-8adc-7887-6d4b-761c47031389" id="_cf801897-8adc-7887-6d4b-761c47031389"></a>By making Procedure an explicit base class rather than a notional reference, EmissionML ensures that its process descriptions are structurally aligned with OMS 3.0 &#x2014; not merely by naming convention, but by class hierarchy. This parallels the Feature/Source pattern: just as Source inherits from Feature to make ISO 19109 alignment concrete, DeterminationProcedure inherits from Procedure to make OMS 3.0 alignment concrete.</p>
</div>
        <div><a name="_5485b01b-eedf-a18b-7d09-2dd27f040c36" id="_5485b01b-eedf-a18b-7d09-2dd27f040c36"></a><h2>B.5.<span style="mso-tab-count:1">&#xA0; </span>Why Explicit Domain Modeling</h2>

<p class="MsoNormal"><a name="_1d6b6e99-0ca1-b88e-84c2-96ba1c0cc612" id="_1d6b6e99-0ca1-b88e-84c2-96ba1c0cc612"></a><b>The alternative.</b> One could model everything with generic Features and Observations &#x2014; Sources as plain Features, emission data as Observation results, and relationships as ad-hoc properties. This approach uses only existing OGC standards without defining new classes.</p>

<p class="MsoNormal"><a name="_8cc412b4-bbb5-7b15-eee7-123c60a79ff0" id="_8cc412b4-bbb5-7b15-eee7-123c60a79ff0"></a><b>The problem.</b> Generic modeling loses domain semantics. Without EmissionML&#x2019;s explicit classes, systems cannot:</p>

<div class="ul_wrap"><p style="mso-list:l3 level1 lfo9;" class="MsoListParagraphCxSpFirst"><a name="_395fb680-e1cd-b643-9212-4ac0397a34f7" id="_395fb680-e1cd-b643-9212-4ac0397a34f7"></a>distinguish a Source from any other Feature,
</p>
<p style="mso-list:l3 level1 lfo9;" class="MsoListParagraphCxSpMiddle"><a name="_ba776354-8350-1421-4ec6-4fdc0a71d5f2" id="_ba776354-8350-1421-4ec6-4fdc0a71d5f2"></a>enforce that an emission has a Mechanism and an Intent,
</p>
<p style="mso-list:l3 level1 lfo9;" class="MsoListParagraphCxSpMiddle"><a name="_901a1cf2-8d64-34af-4799-bcef11d98252" id="_901a1cf2-8d64-34af-4799-bcef11d98252"></a>trace the evidence chain from Observation to Emission Quantity to Emission Event,
</p>
<p style="mso-list:l3 level1 lfo9;" class="MsoListParagraphCxSpLast"><a name="_043cf465-7f88-088d-0308-e06f0f41c606" id="_043cf465-7f88-088d-0308-e06f0f41c606"></a>validate that required relationships are present (e.g., every Emission Event must have a Source, a Mechanism, and a Determination Procedure).
</p>
</div>

<p class="MsoNormal"><a name="_4b5be646-862f-7a97-48e7-85b4745e2f39" id="_4b5be646-862f-7a97-48e7-85b4745e2f39"></a><b>What explicit modeling provides:</b></p>

<table class="dl"><a name="_31774df9-758e-e393-04ce-670e07b623b8" id="_31774df9-758e-e393-04ce-670e07b623b8"></a><tr><td valign="top" align="left"><p align="left" style="margin-left:0pt;text-align:left;" class="MsoNormal">Interoperability</p></td><td valign="top"><p class="MsoNormal"><a name="_d61a5781-b91e-df05-4260-7745f99adf28" id="_d61a5781-b91e-df05-4260-7745f99adf28"></a>Systems exchanging EmissionML data share a common vocabulary. EmissionEvent, Source, Mechanism, and EmissionQuantity are unambiguous &#x2014; they mean the same thing in every implementation.</p>
</td></tr><tr><td valign="top" align="left"><p align="left" style="margin-left:0pt;text-align:left;" class="MsoNormal">Validation</p></td><td valign="top"><p class="MsoNormal"><a name="_b9ce765f-e00f-2e25-e9df-3a47e03845ec" id="_b9ce765f-e00f-2e25-e9df-3a47e03845ec"></a>Requirements can be formally specified and enforced. For example, Requirement 1 mandates that every Emission Event has a Source, a Mechanism, start time, quantity, and their corresponding Determination Procedures.</p>
</td></tr><tr><td valign="top" align="left"><p align="left" style="margin-left:0pt;text-align:left;" class="MsoNormal">Usability</p></td><td valign="top"><p class="MsoNormal"><a name="_87b542d2-a11d-2789-878f-f3d49ff57764" id="_87b542d2-a11d-2789-878f-f3d49ff57764"></a>Domain experts work with emission concepts directly &#x2014; <i>emission events</i>, <i>sources</i>, <i>mechanisms</i> &#x2014; rather than mapping to and from generic abstractions. This reduces the cognitive burden and the risk of misinterpretation.</p>
</td></tr></table>

<p class="MsoNormal"><a name="_cb391e98-062c-cb59-b1dc-93ddfe62a435" id="_cb391e98-062c-cb59-b1dc-93ddfe62a435"></a><b>Analogy.</b> Just as CityGML defines explicit Building, Road, and Vegetation classes rather than using generic Features, EmissionML defines explicit emission domain classes. The General Feature Model provides the abstract foundation; EmissionML provides the domain-specific vocabulary that makes emission data interoperable and actionable.</p>
</div>
      </div>
      <p class="MsoNormal">
        <br clear="all" style="mso-special-character:line-break;page-break-before:always"/>
      </p>
      <div><h1 class="Section3">Bibliography</h1>
<p class="Biblio"><a name="OGC_OMS" id="OGC_OMS"></a>[1]<span style="mso-tab-count:1">&#xA0; </span>Katharina Schleidt, Ilkka Rinne: OGC&#xA0;20-082r4, <i>Topic 20&#x2009;&#x2014;&#x2009;Observations, measurements and samples</i>. Open Geospatial Consortium (2023). <a href="http://www.opengis.net/doc/as/om/3.0">http://www.opengis.net/doc/as/om/3.0</a>.</p><p class="Biblio"><a name="OGC_EmissionML_DP" id="OGC_EmissionML_DP"></a>[2]<span style="mso-tab-count:1">&#xA0; </span>OGC: Introduction to OGC EmissionML: Why the World Needs a Standard Ontology for Emissions. OGC Discussion Paper (2025).</p>


</div>
    </div>
    <div style="mso-element:footnote-list"/>
  </body>
</html>


